<subSubSection pageNumber="663" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="663">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="663">Note:</emphasis>
Mabberley (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="663">Gard. Bull. Singapore</emphasis>
37: 63-64. 1984) provided a detailed account of the history of this taxon and its many cultivars, concluding that its type should be a Clifford sheet. However, this choice is pre-dated by that of Abdulla (and followed by several later authors), who chose Hermann material from Sri Lanka as the type. Despite some confusion over the geographical provenance (Syria vs. Ceylon) of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Meliaceae" genus="Melia" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="species" species="azedarach">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="663">M. azedarach</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and its 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1753" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Meliaceae" genus="Melia" higherTaxonomySource="IPNI" kingdom="Plantae" order="Sapindales" phylum="Magnoliophyta" rank="variety" species="azedarach" variety="sempervirens">
var. 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="663">sempervirens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by Linnaeus, his diagnosis for the species name is firmly linked with the 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="663">
<volumeTitle>Flora Zeylanica</volumeTitle>
</emphasis>
account, and there seem to be no grounds for rejecting 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Abdullaâ€™s">Abdulla's</normalizedToken>
choice. There appear to be no nomenclatural implications at species rank.
</paragraph>
